1H<ue5>18H<ue5>TOUCHUPS<ql>
<styl>by <m0>By JAY ROMANO<ql>
<m1><styl>crline <m0>New York Times Service<ql>
<ep>
   <m2><ql>
<ql>
<m1>E<m2><ql>
<m0>ver visit a used-car lot? If so, you might have noticed that despite differences in price, mileage and mechanical condition, nearly all the cars had one thing in common: a new wax job.<ep>
   Used-car dealers know what sells cars: curb appeal.<ep>
   Used-house dealers know something about curb appeal, too. Real estate experts say sellers can maximize a home's value and minimize time on the market with relatively inexpensive steps.<ep>
   ``People get a feel about a house in the first few seconds,'' said Warren Cronacher, a professional engineer. ``It's either `Bingo!' and there's instant chemistry, or it's, `Oh, that's nice, now let's move on.' ''<ep>
   Indeed, Cronacher said, if a real estate <m2><ql>
<ql>
